summary:
In endomyocardial fibrosis, fibrous tissue restricts regional left ventricular wall motion, particularly at the apex, resulting in reduced contractility; surgical resection removes these obstructions, enabling recovery of more normalized regional motion as detected through objective imaging techniques such as echo or cardiac MRI. This supports a definitive yes—quantitative improvement in regional wall motion is both plausible and clinically observed post-procedure.  

\boxed{A}

The presence of restrictive fibrosis leads to quantifiable impairment in regional left ventricular wall motion due to obstruction (like apex obliteration). Surgical resection alleviates mechanical constraints, allowing for demonstrably improved regional systolic performance measured reliably using echocardiography or cardiac MRI. 

\boxed{A}
